        <section class="section-card">
            <h2>Lumbini</h2>
            <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/frog-hub/frog-hub.github.io/main/images/lumbini.jpg" alt="Lumbini">
            <p>Lumbini, the birthplace of Lord Buddha, is a UNESCO World Heritage Site located in the Rupandehi District of Nepal. This sacred site is home to the Maya Devi Temple, which marks the spot where Queen Maya Devi gave birth to Siddhartha Gautama, who later became the Buddha. The temple complex includes ancient stupas and monasteries, dating back to the 3rd century BC. Visitors can also explore the Ashoka Pillar, erected by Emperor Ashoka in 249 BC to commemorate his pilgrimage to Lumbini. The serene Lumbini Garden, sacred Bodhi Tree, and the tranquil pond add to the spiritual ambiance of this historical landmark.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="section-card">
            <h2>Kathmandu</h2>
            <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/frog-hub/frog-hub.github.io/main/images/kathmandu.jpg" alt="Kathmandu">
            <p>Kathmandu, the bustling capital city of Nepal, is a vibrant mix of history, culture, and modernity. The city's rich heritage is evident in its stunning temples and ancient architecture. Durbar Square, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, is the heart of Kathmandu, featuring palaces, courtyards, and temples like the Hanuman Dhoka, Kumari Ghar, and the Taleju Temple. The Swayambhunath Stupa, also known as the Monkey Temple, offers panoramic views of the city and is a significant pilgrimage site for Buddhists. Pashupatinath Temple, one of the holiest Hindu temples, attracts thousands of devotees each year. Kathmandu's lively markets, traditional Newari cuisine, and vibrant festivals make it a captivating destination for travelers.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="section-card">
            <h2>Mustang</h2>
            <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/frog-hub/frog-hub.github.io/main/images/mustang.jpg" alt="Mustang">
            <p>Mustang, located in the remote northwestern region of Nepal, is a mystical and picturesque destination known for its dramatic landscapes and ancient Tibetan-influenced culture. The Upper Mustang region, also known as the Forbidden Kingdom, was restricted to foreigners until 1992, preserving its unique heritage. The capital of Upper Mustang, Lo Manthang, is a walled city with medieval palaces, monasteries, and traditional Tibetan homes. The region's rugged terrain, deep gorges, and colorful rock formations create a surreal and breathtaking environment. Mustang is also home to the Tiji Festival, a vibrant three-day event celebrated with traditional dances, rituals, and music, symbolizing the triumph of good over evil.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="section-card">
            <h2>Annapurna</h2>
            <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/frog-hub/frog-hub.github.io/main/images/annapurna.jpg" alt="Annapurna">
            <p>The Annapurna region is renowned for its diverse trekking routes, offering stunning views of the Himalayan peaks and a rich variety of ecosystems. The Annapurna Circuit, one of the most popular trekking routes in the world, takes trekkers through lush subtropical forests, terraced farmlands, alpine meadows, and arid deserts. The Annapurna Base Camp trek provides a closer view of the majestic Annapurna massif, including Annapurna I, the tenth highest peak in the world. The region is also home to the Annapurna Conservation Area, a protected area that houses diverse flora and fauna, including rare species like the snow leopard and the red panda. The local Gurung and Thakali cultures add to the rich cultural experience of trekking in the Annapurna region.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="section-card">
            <h2>Badimalika</h2>
            <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/frog-hub/frog-hub.github.io/e537cc6bb5c99f727d8e4c70feb71bed0617f88e/badimalika.jpg" alt="Badimalika">
            <p>Badimalika is a sacred pilgrimage destination located in the Bajura District of western Nepal. The region is known for the Badimalika Temple, dedicated to the Hindu goddess Badimalika. Perched on a ridge at an altitude of 4,200 meters (13,780 feet), the temple offers stunning panoramic views of the surrounding mountains and valleys. The annual Badimalika Festival, held in August, attracts thousands of pilgrims who undertake a challenging trek to reach the temple. The trek to Badimalika passes through lush forests, alpine meadows, and traditional villages, offering a blend of natural beauty and cultural heritage. The temple's remote location and spiritual significance make it a revered site for devotees seeking blessings and peace.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="section-card">
            <h2>Chitwan National Park</h2>
            <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/frog-hub/frog-hub.github.io/main/images/chitwan.jpg" alt="Chitwan National Park">
            <p>Chitwan National Park, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, is Nepal's first national park and a renowned wildlife sanctuary. Located in the subtropical Terai lowlands, the park spans 932 square kilometers (360 square miles) and is home to a diverse range of wildlife, including the endangered one-horned rhinoceros, Bengal tiger, Asian elephant, and gharial crocodile. The park offers a variety of safari experiences, including jeep safaris, elephant-back rides, and guided jungle walks. Visitors can also enjoy birdwatching, with over 500 bird species recorded in the park. The indigenous Tharu community, known for their vibrant culture and traditions, resides in the buffer zones around the park, adding to the rich cultural experience of visiting Chitwan National Park.</p>
        </section>
        <section class="section-card">
            <h2>Janakpur</h2>
            <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/frog-hub/frog-hub.github.io/main/images/janakpur.jpg" alt="Janakpur">
            <p>Janakpur, located in the southeastern plains of Nepal, is a historical and religious city with deep significance in Hindu mythology. The city is renowned for the Janaki Mandir, a grand temple dedicated to Goddess Sita, the consort of Lord Rama. Built in a unique Mughal and Rajput architectural style, the temple is one of the largest and most beautiful in Nepal. Janakpur is believed to be the birthplace of Sita, and it is here that she married Lord Rama, making the city an important pilgrimage site for Hindus. The city is also known for the Vivah Panchami festival, celebrated with great enthusiasm to commemorate the divine marriage of Sita and Rama. Visitors can explore other historical sites, sacred ponds, and vibrant markets that reflect the rich cultural heritage of Janakpur.</p>
        </section>
